The `boot()` function creates a new jiki container. It sets up the virtual filesystem, kernel, and shell.

## Signature

```ts
import { boot } from "@run0/jiki";

const container = await boot(options?: BootOptions);
```

## Options

| Option        | Type                     | Default     | Description                                                               |
| ------------- | ------------------------ | ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `cwd`         | `string`                 | `"/"`       | Initial working directory                                                 |
| `env`         | `Record<string, string>` | `{}`        | Environment variables                                                     |
| `snapshot`    | `Uint8Array`             | `undefined` | Restore from a previously saved snapshot                                  |
| `plugins`     | `JikiPlugin[]`           | `[]`        | [Plugins](/docs/api/plugins) to register on the container                 |
| `persistence` | `PersistenceAdapter`     | `undefined` | [Persistence](/docs/api/persistence) adapter for surviving page refreshes |

## Return value

Returns a `Promise<Container>` that resolves when the container is ready.

## Example

```ts
import { boot } from "@run0/jiki";

const container = await boot({
  cwd: "/app",
  env: { NODE_ENV: "development" },
});

await container.fs.writeFile("/app/index.js", 'console.log("ready")');
await container.shell.execute("node index.js");
```

The `DevServer` class manages HTTP server instances running inside a jiki container. When a framework like Vite or Next.js starts a development server, the DevServer intercepts the `listen()` call and registers the server handler so that requests can be routed to it through the Service Worker bridge.

DevServer tracks all active server instances and their ports. Your application can listen for when a server is ready and route preview iframe traffic to the correct handler. It also manages HMR WebSocket connections for live reloading.

## Methods

| Method                | Description                          |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| `on(event, callback)` | Listen for server lifecycle events   |
| `getUrl(port)`        | Get the preview URL for a given port |

## Events

| Event     | Description                              |
| --------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `"port"`  | Fired when a new server starts listening |
| `"close"` | Fired when a server stops                |

## Example

```ts
container.devServer.on("port", (port, url) => {
  console.log(`Server ready at ${url}`);
  iframe.src = url;
});

await container.shell.spawn("npm", ["run", "dev"]);
```

jiki provides structured error types for failures that occur during container operations. Each error type corresponds to a specific failure category, so you can catch and handle them individually.

Errors thrown by jiki extend a common `JikiError` base class with a `code` property for programmatic matching and a `message` string. Filesystem errors use Node.js conventions like `ENOENT` and `EACCES`.

## Error types

| Error Class         | Code        | Description                                            |
| ------------------- | ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| `FileNotFoundError` | `ENOENT`    | The specified file or directory does not exist         |
| `FileExistsError`   | `EEXIST`    | A file or directory already exists at the path         |
| `PermissionError`   | `EACCES`    | Insufficient permissions for the operation             |
| `ProcessError`      | `PROCESS`   | A shell command or process exited with a non-zero code |
| `TranspileError`    | `TRANSPILE` | esbuild failed to transform the code                   |
| `NetworkError`      | `NETWORK`   | A package download or registry request failed          |

## Error fix suggestions

Parsed errors include an actionable `suggestions` array that helps users fix common mistakes:

```ts
import { parseError } from "@run0/jiki";

const err = parseError("runtime", new Error("Cannot find module 'react'"));
console.log(err.suggestions);
// ["Run: npm install react"]
```

| Error Pattern                    | Suggestion                                |
| -------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `Cannot find module 'X'`         | `Run: npm install X`                      |
| `X is not defined` (capitalized) | `Did you forget to import X?`             |
| `Transpiler not initialized`     | `Call await container.init()`             |
| Sandbox path violations          | `Add the path to sandbox.fs.allowedPaths` |
| Network failures during install  | `Check your internet connection`          |

## `ContainerError`

```ts
interface ContainerError {
  id: string;
  category: "build" | "runtime" | "bundle" | "install" | "filesystem";
  title: string;
  message: string;
  file?: string;
  line?: number;
  column?: number;
  stack?: string;
  suggestions?: string[];
  timestamp: number;
}
```

## Example

```ts
import { FileNotFoundError } from "@run0/jiki";

try {
  await container.readFile("/missing.txt");
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    console.log("File not found:", err.path);
  }
}
```

The `Metrics` class tracks timing and counts for key operations. Every container has a `metrics` instance.

## Quick start

```ts
const container = boot();
container.writeFile("/test.js", 'console.log("hi")');
container.readFile("/test.js");
await container.run("echo hello");

const m = container.getMetrics();
console.log(m.vfsWriteCount); // 1
console.log(m.vfsReadCount); // 1
console.log(m.commandCount); // 1
```

## `MetricsSnapshot`

```ts
interface MetricsSnapshot {
  resolveCount: number;
  resolveTimeMs: number;
  transpileCount: number;
  transpileTimeMs: number;
  vfsReadCount: number;
  vfsWriteCount: number;
  cacheHits: number;
  cacheMisses: number;
  cacheHitRate: number; // 0–1
  commandCount: number;
  installCount: number;
  installTimeMs: number;
  startedAt: number;
  uptimeMs: number;
}
```

## Methods

| Method                      | Description                 |
| --------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| `container.getMetrics()`    | Returns a `MetricsSnapshot` |
| `container.metrics.reset()` | Reset all counters          |

## What gets tracked

| Operation               | Metric                          |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| `container.writeFile()` | `vfsWriteCount`                 |
| `container.readFile()`  | `vfsReadCount`                  |
| `container.run()`       | `commandCount`                  |
| `container.install()`   | `installCount`, `installTimeMs` |

The `NetworkInterceptor` intercepts and mocks outgoing `fetch()` calls. Useful for testing, offline scenarios, and CORS avoidance.

## Quick start

```ts
const container = boot();

// Static mock
container.mockFetch("/api/users", { json: [{ name: "Alice" }] });

// Dynamic handler
container.onFetch(url => {
  if (url.includes("/health")) return { json: { ok: true } };
  return null; // pass through
});
```

## `MockResponse`

```ts
interface MockResponse {
  status?: number; // default: 200
  headers?: Record<string, string>;
  body?: string;
  json?: unknown; // auto-serialized, overrides body
}
```

## Container methods

| Method                         | Description                             |
| ------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- |
| `mockFetch(pattern, response)` | Register static mock (string or RegExp) |
| `onFetch(handler)`             | Register dynamic handler                |
| `network.clear()`              | Remove all rules and handlers           |
| `network.ruleCount`            | Number of static rules                  |
| `network.handlerCount`         | Number of dynamic handlers              |

## Matching order

1. Static rules are checked first (first match wins)
2. Dynamic handlers are checked in registration order
3. If nothing matches, the request passes through to the real network

## `mockResponseToFetchResponse`

Converts a `MockResponse` to a fetch-compatible object:

```ts
import { mockResponseToFetchResponse } from "@run0/jiki";

const resp = mockResponseToFetchResponse({ json: { ok: true } });
await resp.json(); // { ok: true }
```

The `Shell` class runs shell commands within a jiki container. It parses command strings, resolves executables, and manages process I/O.

The shell supports standard Unix-like syntax including pipes, logical operators, and environment variable expansion. Commands are executed against the virtual filesystem and kernel, so tools like `node`, `npm`, and `npx` work as expected.

## Methods

| Method                            | Description                    |
| --------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `execute(command)`                | Execute a shell command string |
| `spawn(command, args?, options?)` | Spawn a long-running process   |

## Execute result

The `execute()` method returns a promise that resolves with the command's result:

```ts
interface ShellResult {
  exitCode: number;
  stdout: string;
  stderr: string;
}
```

## Spawn

For long-running processes like dev servers, use `spawn()` which returns a process handle with streaming I/O:

```ts
const proc = await container.shell.spawn("npm", ["run", "dev"]);

proc.stdout.on("data", chunk => {
  console.log(chunk);
});

await proc.exit; // wait for process to finish
```

The `Transpiler` class handles TypeScript, JSX, and TSX transpilation using esbuild-wasm. It can also bundle files with tree-shaking and minification.

The transpiler lazily loads the esbuild WebAssembly binary on first use. Once initialized, subsequent transformations are fast since the WASM runtime stays warm in memory. The transpiler is used internally by the kernel for `require()` calls but can also be used directly for explicit build tasks.

## Methods

| Method                      | Description                           |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `transform(code, options?)` | Transform a single file's code        |
| `build(options)`            | Bundle multiple files into one output |
| `initialize()`              | Eagerly load the esbuild WASM binary  |

## Transform options

```ts
interface TransformOptions {
  loader?: "ts" | "tsx" | "jsx" | "js";
  sourcemap?: boolean | "inline";
  minify?: boolean;
  target?: string;
  jsx?: "transform" | "preserve" | "automatic";
}
```

## Example

```ts
const result = await container.transpiler.transform(
  `const greet = (name: string): string => \`Hello, \${name}\`;`,
  { loader: "ts", sourcemap: true },
);

console.log(result.code);
// 'const greet = (name) => `Hello, ${name}`;\n'
```

The `TypeChecker` provides on-demand type checking for TypeScript files in the VFS using heuristic-based analysis. It catches common errors without requiring the full TypeScript compiler.

## Quick start

```ts
import { boot, TypeChecker } from "@run0/jiki";

const container = boot();
container.writeFile(
  "/src/app.ts",
  `
  const x: any = 42;
  function greet(name) {
    return "Hello " + name;
    console.log("unreachable");
  }
`,
);

const checker = new TypeChecker(container.vfs);
const diagnostics = checker.checkAll("/src");

for (const d of diagnostics) {
  console.log(`${d.file}:${d.line} [${d.severity}] ${d.message}`);
}
```

## API

### `new TypeChecker(vfs, options?)`

| Option           | Type      | Default         | Description                |
| ---------------- | --------- | --------------- | -------------------------- |
| `strict`         | `boolean` | `true`          | Enable strict checks       |
| `noUnusedLocals` | `boolean` | `false`         | Check for unused variables |
| `noImplicitAny`  | `boolean` | `true` (strict) | Warn on `any` usage        |

### `checker.check(files)`

Check specific files. Returns `Diagnostic[]` sorted by file and line.

### `checker.checkAll(dir?)`

Discover all `.ts`/`.tsx` files in a directory and check them. Default: `/src`.

### `Diagnostic`

```ts
interface Diagnostic {
  file: string;
  line: number;
  column: number;
  message: string;
  severity: "error" | "warning" | "info";
  code?: string;
}
```

## What it detects

- Explicit `any` usage (when `noImplicitAny` is enabled)
- Unreachable code after `return`/`throw`
- Missing return type annotations on exported functions
- Duplicate variable declarations in the same scope
- Missing files

For full type checking, install TypeScript and run `npx tsc --noEmit` via the shell.

Workspace support for monorepos. Discovers packages from `package.json` workspaces or `pnpm-workspace.yaml` and creates symlinks for cross-package resolution.

## Discovering workspaces

```ts
import { discoverWorkspaces } from "@run0/jiki";

const workspaces = discoverWorkspaces(container.vfs, "/");
// [{ name: '@app/utils', path: '/packages/utils', version: '1.0.0' }]
```

Reads workspace patterns from:

- `package.json` → `"workspaces": ["packages/*"]`
- `pnpm-workspace.yaml` → `packages: ['packages/*']`

Glob patterns supported: `packages/*`, `apps/**`

## Linking workspaces

```ts
import { linkWorkspaces } from "@run0/jiki";

linkWorkspaces(container.vfs, "/", workspaces);
// Creates symlinks: /node_modules/@app/utils → /packages/utils
```

## Resolving workspace: Protocol

```ts
import { isWorkspaceProtocol, resolveWorkspaceDep } from "@run0/jiki";

isWorkspaceProtocol("workspace:*"); // true
isWorkspaceProtocol("^1.0.0"); // false

const dep = resolveWorkspaceDep("@app/utils", workspaces);
// { name: '@app/utils', path: '/packages/utils', version: '1.0.0' }
```

## `WorkspacePackage`

```ts
interface WorkspacePackage {
  name: string; // package name
  path: string; // absolute path in VFS
  version: string; // version from package.json
}
```

By default, every `container.install()` call fetches package metadata and tarballs from the npm registry over the network. The package cache keeps previously-fetched data in memory so repeat installs are near-instant.

Manifests are cached with a configurable TTL (default 1 hour) since they can change when new versions are published. Tarballs are cached indefinitely because npm tarball URLs are immutable (content-addressed).

## How it works

1. On the first install, manifests and tarballs are fetched from the registry and stored in the cache.
2. On repeat installs, the cache serves manifests (if within TTL) and tarballs directly, skipping network requests entirely.
3. If a manifest has expired or a tarball hasn't been seen before, it's fetched from the registry and cached.

Every `PackageManager` gets its own `PackageCache` instance by default. You can also share a cache across multiple package managers or pass a pre-populated cache.

## Quick start

The cache works automatically with no configuration needed:

```ts
import { boot } from "@run0/jiki";

const container = boot();

// First install: fetches from registry
await container.install("react");

// Second install: served from cache (near-instant)
await container.install("react-dom"); // react manifest is already cached
```

## Custom configuration

```ts
import { boot, PackageCache } from "@run0/jiki";

const cache = new PackageCache({
  manifestTtlMs: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes instead of 1 hour
  maxManifests: 1000, // default: 500
  maxTarballs: 500, // default: 200
});

const container = boot();
// Access the cache via container.packageManager.cache
container.packageManager.clearCache(); // clear when needed
```

## Diagnostics

```ts
const { cache } = container.packageManager;

cache.manifestCount; // number of cached manifests
cache.tarballCount; // number of cached tarballs
cache.tarballBytes; // total bytes of cached tarballs
```

## Clearing the cache

```ts
// Clear everything
container.packageManager.clearCache();

// Or selectively
container.packageManager.cache.clearManifests();
container.packageManager.cache.clearTarballs();
```

## Cache eviction

When the cache reaches its size limits, the oldest entries are evicted automatically:

| Store        | Default limit | Eviction                  |
| ------------ | ------------- | ------------------------- |
| Manifests    | 500 entries   | Oldest by insertion order |
| Tarballs     | 200 entries   | Oldest by insertion order |
| Manifest TTL | 1 hour        | Re-fetched on next access |

By default, jiki's virtual filesystem lives entirely in memory, so every page refresh wipes all files, installed packages, and user state. The persistence layer fixes this by automatically synchronising filesystem mutations to a storage backend (IndexedDB by default), so the VFS can be rehydrated on the next boot.

## How it works

1. When a file is created, updated, deleted, renamed, or symlinked, the mutation is queued for persistence.
2. Queued mutations are flushed to IndexedDB in batches (~100 ms) to minimise transaction overhead. Writes are fire-and-forget and never block the synchronous VFS API.
3. Calling `container.init()` (or `vfs.hydrate()` directly) loads all persisted entries back into memory, restoring the filesystem to its previous state.

## Quick start

```ts
import { boot, IndexedDBAdapter } from "@run0/jiki";

const adapter = new IndexedDBAdapter({ dbName: "my-project" });
const container = boot({ persistence: adapter });
await container.init();

// Files written now will survive page refreshes
container.writeFile("/app/index.js", 'console.log("persisted!");');
```

After a page refresh, the same code will restore `/app/index.js` from IndexedDB before the transpiler initialises.

## Adapters

### `IndexedDBAdapter`

The default browser-compatible adapter. Uses a single IndexedDB object store keyed by normalised path.

```ts
import { IndexedDBAdapter } from "@run0/jiki";

const adapter = new IndexedDBAdapter({
  dbName: "my-project", // default: "jiki-vfs"
  storeName: "files", // default: "files"
  flushIntervalMs: 100, // default: 100
});
```

| Option            | Type     | Default      | Description                |
| ----------------- | -------- | ------------ | -------------------------- |
| `dbName`          | `string` | `"jiki-vfs"` | IndexedDB database name    |
| `storeName`       | `string` | `"files"`    | Object store name          |
| `flushIntervalMs` | `number` | `100`        | Batch flush interval in ms |

### `InMemoryAdapter`

Stores entries in a `Map`. Useful for testing and server-side environments where IndexedDB is unavailable.

```ts
import { InMemoryAdapter } from "@run0/jiki";

const adapter = new InMemoryAdapter();
```

### Custom adapters

Implement the `PersistenceAdapter` interface to use any storage backend (OPFS, localStorage, a remote server, etc.):

```ts
import type { PersistenceAdapter, PersistedEntry } from "@run0/jiki";

class MyAdapter implements PersistenceAdapter {
  save(entry: PersistedEntry): void {
    /* upsert */
  }
  delete(path: string): void {
    /* remove */
  }
  async loadAll(): Promise<PersistedEntry[]> {
    /* read all */
  }
  async clear(): Promise<void> {
    /* wipe */
  }
  async flush(): Promise<void> {
    /* force write */
  }
}
```

## Hydration

Call `container.init()` to hydrate from the adapter. Hydration restores files, directories, and symlinks in depth-first order. It runs before the transpiler initialises, so TypeScript files are ready when code execution starts.

```ts
const container = boot({ persistence: adapter });
const count = await container.init(); // restores persisted files
```

You can also call `vfs.hydrate()` directly if you need more control:

```ts
const vfs = new MemFS({ persistence: adapter });
const count = await vfs.hydrate();
console.log(`Restored ${count} entries`);
```

## Flushing

Persistence writes are batched and flushed automatically. To force an immediate flush (e.g. before page unload):

```ts
await container.vfs.flushPersistence();
```

## What gets persisted

| Operation                     | Persisted?                                                  |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| `writeFileSync` / `writeFile` | Yes                                                         |
| `symlinkSync`                 | Yes                                                         |
| `unlinkSync`                  | Yes (removed)                                               |
| `rmdirSync` (recursive)       | Yes (tree removed)                                          |
| `renameSync`                  | Yes (old removed, new saved)                                |
| `mkdirSync`                   | No (directories are recreated on hydration from file paths) |
| `putFile(path, data, false)`  | No (used during hydration)                                  |

## Performance

- Batch writes reduce IndexedDB transaction overhead. Rapid consecutive writes (e.g. installing 100 packages) result in a few large transactions instead of 100 small ones.
- Hydration reads all entries in a single `getAll()` call, which is the fastest way to bulk-read from IndexedDB.
- Memory is not doubled: persisted entries are written to IndexedDB asynchronously and not kept in a separate in-memory store.

Plugins let you intercept and extend jiki's behaviour at key points in the runtime lifecycle without modifying core code. The plugin API mirrors esbuild's conventions, so it should feel familiar if you've written esbuild or Vite plugins before.

Each container gets its own plugin registry, so plugins registered on one container never leak into another.

## What plugins can do

- Intercept module specifiers and redirect them to custom paths (resolve hooks)
- Provide virtual file contents without writing to the filesystem (load hooks)
- Modify source code before execution, with all matching transforms running in order (transform hooks)
- Register custom shell commands
- React to boot and package install events

## How it works

When you pass a `plugins` array to `boot()`, each plugin's `setup()` function is called during container construction. Inside `setup()`, you register hooks that the runtime calls at the appropriate points:

1. When `require("some-module")` is called, `onResolve` hooks run first. If a hook returns a path, the default resolver is skipped entirely.
2. Once a path is resolved, `onLoad` hooks run before the filesystem is read. If a hook returns contents, the VFS read is skipped.
3. After source code is loaded (from a plugin or the VFS), `onTransform` hooks run as a pipeline. Every matching hook gets to modify the code in registration order.
4. The final transformed code is evaluated by the kernel.

## Quick example

```ts
import { boot, type JikiPlugin } from "@run0/jiki";

const envPlugin: JikiPlugin = {
  name: "env-injector",
  setup(hooks) {
    hooks.onResolve(/^@env$/, () => ({ path: "/__env__.js" }));
    hooks.onLoad(/^\/__env__\.js$/, () => ({
      contents: `module.exports = ${JSON.stringify({
        NODE_ENV: "development",
        API_URL: "https://api.example.com",
      })};`,
    }));
  },
};

const container = boot({ plugins: [envPlugin] });
container.writeFile(
  "/app.js",
  `
  const env = require("@env");
  console.log(env.API_URL);
`,
);
container.runFile("/app.js");
```

## Hook execution semantics

| Hook          | Semantics                                                                            |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `onResolve`   | First match wins — first callback to return a result stops the chain                 |
| `onLoad`      | First match wins                                                                     |
| `onTransform` | Pipeline — all matching callbacks run in registration order                          |
| `onCommand`   | Registered on the shell; later registrations for the same name override earlier ones |
| `onInstall`   | All callbacks called after packages are installed                                    |
| `onBoot`      | All callbacks called after `container.init()`                                        |

See the [Plugins API reference](/docs/api/plugins) for the full type signatures, and the [Writing Plugins guide](/docs/guides/plugins) for practical patterns.

MemFS is jiki's in-memory filesystem with Node.js-compatible semantics. It supports file operations, directories, symlinks, file watching, and snapshot serialization.

Because all file data lives in memory, reads and writes are fast. The API surface matches the standard Node.js `fs` module, which is what allows jiki to run Node.js-like toolchains without access to a real disk.

## Basic usage

```ts
import { boot } from "@run0/jiki";

const container = await boot();

// Write a file
await container.fs.writeFile("/index.js", 'console.log("Hello, jiki!")');

// Read a file
const content = await container.fs.readFile("/index.js", "utf-8");
console.log(content); // 'console.log("Hello, jiki!")'

// Create directories
await container.fs.mkdir("/src", { recursive: true });

// List directory contents
const files = await container.fs.readdir("/");
```

## Supported operations

The filesystem covers the operations you'd expect from a Node.js `fs` module: reading, writing, appending, renaming, copying, and deleting files. You can create and remove directories recursively, create and resolve symbolic links, and watch files or directories for changes. The entire filesystem state can also be serialized to a snapshot and restored later.

